<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-827-254  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 827 254.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  Oct 30 1989 v35 n1782 p36(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Army plans to expand digital drawing system. (the ComputerAutomated Logistics System)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Robertson, Jack.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Army will expand its Computer Automated Logistics System(CALS) digital engineering drawings from the LHX helicopterprogram to 27 other weapons systems, according to CALS Program MgrEdward Willis speaking at the Federal Computer Conference inWashington, DC, in late Oct 1989.andP;  Among the other programs thatwill use CALS are the Patriot missile, ASAS intelligence datasystem, AH-64 helicopter multistage improvement, Lance Follow-onmissile, Sincgars radio, Wide Area Mines, Non-Line-of-Sight airdefense missile, and the Medium and Heavy versions of theAnti-Armor Weapon System.andP;  CALS will be a totally paperlessdrawing system that will store all data in digital format for useat each stage of the procurement process when it is fullyimplemented.andP;  Four firms were selected in Jun 1989 to do 12-monthparallel competitive design studies: BDM, Computer Sciences Corp,TRW and Xerox.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Government AgencyMilitaryPurchasing SystemsAutomationResearch and DevelopmentUnited States. ArmyWeapons systemsComputer-aided engineeringLogistics.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>